The uniform provisions you're asking about are detailed in the document BOE-A-2009-2313  specifically in Article 15. According to this document  the company must provide the following uniform items to operational staff every two years starting from the second year:  - Three summer polo shirts - One fleece - Two summer pants - One vest - Three winter polo shirts - Two winter pants - Two pairs of shoes  In addition  for services in outdoor environments  the company must provide suitable waterproof and insulated garments. The uniform delivery can take place at the time of hiring the worker or at the time of changing wardrobe for the season.  Regarding the distribution of uniforms  the company and the representatives of the workers will form a commission. This commission will ensure the strict compliance of the criteria agreed upon in the Health and Safety Committee for the uniform supply. The commission will also be consulted for the allocation of non-regulated items that may be necessary due to the nature of the job  as well as the specific adaptation of the approved uniform to the climatic conditions of the area.  I hope this information is helpful to you.

Mientras que los clientes profesionales suelen tener la capacidad de evaluar adecuadamente los riesgos asociados con los CFD  los clientes minoristas a menudo carecen de esta habilidad. Esto ha llevado a preocupaciones significativas sobre la protección de los inversores  especialmente cuando se ofrecen niveles más altos de apalancamiento a clientes minoristas y se les permite acceder a productos que  por sus características  no deben ser distribuidos a ellos. Based on the provided context information  the text mentions cosmetic products  specifically addressing various aspects related to these products. In addition to the previously mentioned labeling requirements  the text also outlines rules for product advertising. According to the text  any claims made in the advertising  labeling  or promotional materials for cosmetic products must not attribute characteristics  properties  or actions to the products that they do not possess or that exceed their intended cosmetic functions. This includes any claims that are false or likely to mislead the consumer.  Moreover  the text includes a provision regarding the use of language in the labeling and advertising of cosmetic products. Any reference to testing on animals must clearly indicate whether the testing was conducted on the finished product and/or its ingredients. Additionally  the product names must not cause confusion with medications  pharmaceutical specialties  or food products. The packaging and presentation of these products should also prevent confusion with food or other consumer products to avoid potential health risks.  Lastly  public authorities are responsible for monitoring and enforcing the truthfulness of commercial advertising and propaganda  ensuring that they do not negatively impact health.  Document reference: <https://www.boe.es/buscar/
